<div class="post-body rv">
<h2>Why B2B Social Media Is Different</h2>
<p>Most social media frameworks are built for consumer brands - high frequency, reach-optimised content designed to grow audiences. When enterprise B2B brands apply the same logic, they almost always fail: wrong platforms, wrong tone, wrong metrics, wrong outcome. B2B social media has a different job: building credibility with a small, specific audience of decision-makers who are evaluating you as a potential partner.</p>
<div class="stat-bar"><div class="stat-bar-item"><div class="stat-bar-n">97%</div><div class="stat-bar-l">Of B2B marketers use LinkedIn</div></div><div class="stat-bar-item"><div class="stat-bar-n">5.1x</div><div class="stat-bar-l">More likely to convert LinkedIn leads</div></div><div class="stat-bar-item"><div class="stat-bar-n">80%</div><div class="stat-bar-l">Of B2B leads come from LinkedIn</div></div></div>
<h2>Platform Strategy for Enterprise B2B</h2>
<p>LinkedIn is the primary platform for thought leadership, case studies, and paid demand generation. X/Twitter is valuable for real-time industry commentary in specific sectors. YouTube is the most underutilised B2B platform - long-form video content has outstanding SEO value and dwell time. Instagram is secondary for culture and brand building, not direct pipeline generation.</p>
<div class="pull-quote"><p>"The best B2B social content does not sell. It teaches, challenges, or reveals. The pipeline follows from the trust that content builds."</p></div>
<h2>Content That Actually Converts</h2>
<p>After managing enterprise B2B social programmes for dozens of clients, the content types that consistently generate pipeline are: original research and data to establish authority, behind-the-scenes process content to build trust and differentiation, client outcome stories with specific numbers for proof of performance, and executive personal branding to humanise the organisation. The content that tends not to work: promotional product announcements without context and generic industry news commentary.</p>
<h2>Measuring What Matters</h2>
<p>Vanity metrics are not the right success criteria for B2B social. We track three metrics that connect to business outcomes: profile views from target ICP job titles, website visits from social with sessions over two minutes, and content-influenced pipeline where social content appears in the attribution path. These numbers tell a story that boards understand.</p>
